<tr><td width="100%" colspan="3"><table border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="2"><tr><td width="50%" valign="top"><font face="Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular" size="2"><b>Editor's Note:</b><br>We at Vitacost would like to thank all of the readers of this newsletter who have expressed their gratitude and support for our stand against the flawed study published in JAMA on April 19, 2001 regarding St. John's wort and depression.  For those of you who have not read the original newsletter or the subsequent correspondences <a href="http://rd.mailshell.com/aar51ym@mailshell.com/www.vitacost.com/newsletter/html41901.html"><b>CLICK HERE</b></a>.</td><td width="0"></td><td width="50%" valign="top"><font face="Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular" size="2"><b>Greetings:</b><br>In a recently published study, it was reported that a diet deficient in the trace mineral selenium may result in a worse case of the flu (in an animal study).  You might ask, what would a trace mineral have to do with the flu?  It's quite simple.  It all relates to immune function.  Researchers are learning more and more about the importance of trace minerals and other nutrients in helping to optimize cell function.  Up to thirty years ago, researchers did not even realize that selenium was an essential nutrient required for our body.  It has now been discovered that selenium is a powerful anti-oxidant that not only can help ward off a bad case of the flu, but maybe even cancer.</font></td>
